# Practical 01 - DFS and BFS Algorithm

## Aim
To implement DFS (Depth First Search) and BFS (Breadth First Search) algorithms using an undirected graph and perform recursive traversal of all vertices.

---

## Theory

Graph traversal is the process of visiting all vertices in a graph.

### 1. Breadth First Search (BFS)
BFS visits nodes level by level starting from the source node.

- Uses Queue data structure
- Explores nearest nodes first
- Useful in shortest path problems

### 2. Depth First Search (DFS)
DFS explores as far as possible along one branch before backtracking.

- Uses recursion or stack
- Traverses depth-wise
- Useful in path finding and tree traversal

---

## Applications
- Artificial Intelligence
- Web Crawling
- Network Analysis
- Path Finding
- Social Networks

---

## Algorithm for BFS
1. Start from source node
2. Mark node as visited
3. Insert node into queue
4. Remove node from queue
5. Visit all unvisited adjacent nodes
6. Repeat until queue becomes empty

---

## Algorithm for DFS
1. Start from source node
2. Mark node as visited
3. Visit adjacent unvisited nodes recursively
4. Repeat until all nodes are visited